snippet.textDisplay:
The problem is, all the time you have Soleimani in position, you know who you're dealing with. No matter how hardline he appears to his people and political enemies, as he has to be, you still have someone you can negotiate with, whose strengths and point of view you are familiar with. Take him away and who fills the vacuum? In an environment of fear and extreme anger like we are seeing in Iran at the moment, the more accessible leaders are pushed aside and the hardline, fanatical zealots, supported by popular opinion, step forward.
Ever since the humiliation of Vietnam, American presidents have wanted to be THE wartime president, to follow in Roosevelt and Wilsons footsteps. 'To right the wrong' and go down in history as the man who changed the course of history. In their time, the American army faced the world's best military of its day, the German Army. Today there are no such certainties of army to army war. Now we have suicide bombings, infrastructure attacks, cyber warfare. And the fanatics won't worry if you bomb them back to the Stone Age, they'll continue the war against you.
Only time will tell if Trump acted foolishly or not.
